WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.275 --> 00:00:09.140
BRADLEY HOROWITZ:
So Kenny Werner

00:00:09.140 --> 00:00:11.390
has been a world-class
pianist and composer

00:00:11.390 --> 00:00:12.710
for more than 40 years.

00:00:12.710 --> 00:00:16.550
And I have known him for
about the last 20 years.

00:00:16.550 --> 00:00:19.580
And that very, very
generous introduction

00:00:19.580 --> 00:00:22.190
classified me as a musician.

00:00:22.190 --> 00:00:23.570
That's a stretch.

00:00:23.570 --> 00:00:26.870
I did play music and
even perform music--

00:00:26.870 --> 00:00:32.240
high on passion and
the effortless part,

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:35.690
less so on the mastery
and musicianship part.

00:00:35.690 --> 00:00:37.760
And in the same way,
Kenny, as far as I know,

00:00:37.760 --> 00:00:40.700
unless he's holding back,
is not a computer scientist.

00:00:40.700 --> 00:00:43.790
But somehow we have
forged this friendship

00:00:43.790 --> 00:00:46.620
based on respect for
each other's disciplines.

00:00:46.620 --> 00:00:48.980
And that's really why I'm
so excited to bring him here

00:00:48.980 --> 00:00:49.970
to YouTube today.

00:00:49.970 --> 00:00:52.640
It's because I think
what he's offering is not

00:00:52.640 --> 00:00:54.110
only about music.

00:00:54.110 --> 00:00:56.840
Incredible music is created,
but it's about much,

00:00:56.840 --> 00:00:58.330
much more than music.

00:00:58.330 --> 00:01:02.660
It's about bringing this quality
to all aspects of our work

00:01:02.660 --> 00:01:04.069
and all aspects of our lives.

00:01:04.069 --> 00:01:07.070
And I hope you tune into that.

00:01:07.070 --> 00:01:09.860
Kenny wrote his
landmark book in 1996,

00:01:09.860 --> 00:01:13.260
"Effortless Mastery, Liberating
the Master Musician Within."

00:01:13.260 --> 00:01:15.550
And we have a limited
number of copies over there.

00:01:15.550 --> 00:01:17.440
I'm sorry we don't
have one for everyone.

00:01:17.440 --> 00:01:21.290
But if you're deeply curious,
please help yourself to a copy

00:01:21.290 --> 00:01:23.210
after the performance.

00:01:23.210 --> 00:01:27.230
And it's widely read and studied
amongst musicians everywhere,

00:01:27.230 --> 00:01:29.120
but especially young musicians.

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:32.210
And you heard that the Oakland
School of the Arts is here.

00:01:32.210 --> 00:01:34.550
I wanted to share a little
bit about the story of how

00:01:34.550 --> 00:01:36.170
they got here.

00:01:36.170 --> 00:01:39.680
Kenny is a mentor to a
young student there, Lucas.

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:41.760
Lucas, would you please stand?

00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:43.110
All right.

00:01:43.110 --> 00:01:45.310
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:45.310 --> 00:01:48.660
And so we gave a special
welcome to those students,

00:01:48.660 --> 00:01:51.920
and I couldn't be more
delighted that they are here.

00:01:51.920 --> 00:01:54.890
As you guys all know,
Kenny has a prolific output

00:01:54.890 --> 00:01:57.570
of compositions,
recording, publications.

00:01:57.570 --> 00:02:01.070
He's an incredible musician
as well as educator.

00:02:01.070 --> 00:02:04.359
The qualities of his work--
what I really love is not only

00:02:04.359 --> 00:02:06.650
listening to Kenny-- and I've
had the chance to see him

00:02:06.650 --> 00:02:09.060
perform in many, many settings--

00:02:09.060 --> 00:02:10.430
but also watching Kenny.

00:02:10.430 --> 00:02:14.750
I think while he performs, he
really embodies these qualities

00:02:14.750 --> 00:02:17.450
that he's teaching us--
the effortless part,

00:02:17.450 --> 00:02:21.770
the spontaneity, the
joy, the fearlessness,

00:02:21.770 --> 00:02:22.700
and the discipline.

00:02:22.700 --> 00:02:25.750
All of that is sort of manifest
as you watch Kenny perform,

00:02:25.750 --> 00:02:28.940
and so I'm super happy
to share that with you.

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:32.420
As you may or may not know,
we will have a special guest

00:02:32.420 --> 00:02:35.590
joining Kenny for at least
part of the performance,

00:02:35.590 --> 00:02:39.050
vocalist Claudia
Villela from Brazil,

00:02:39.050 --> 00:02:41.480
who will also demonstrate
some of her amazing gifts

00:02:41.480 --> 00:02:42.870
and techniques as well.

00:02:42.870 --> 00:02:44.960
So without further
ado, let me welcome

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:47.372
to the stage, Kenny Werner.

00:02:47.372 --> 00:02:50.228
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:51.449 --> 00:02:53.615
KENNY WERNER: I thought it
was kind of interesting--

00:02:53.615 --> 00:02:56.390
Sara Beth's introduction
of Bradley--

00:02:56.390 --> 00:02:58.882
he did all these things that
actually changed the world.

00:02:58.882 --> 00:03:00.590
But the most interesting
thing is he used

00:03:00.590 --> 00:03:02.510
to be a musician from Detroit.

00:03:02.510 --> 00:03:03.500
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:03.500 --> 00:03:05.790
I somehow think the most
interesting thing is--

00:03:05.790 --> 00:03:07.480
there's some other interesting
things about Bradley.

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:08.060
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:08.060 --> 00:03:10.220
So I'm going to play
something first,

00:03:10.220 --> 00:03:13.830
and then I may be speaking.

00:03:13.830 --> 00:03:15.959
It's a distinct possibility.

00:03:19.951 --> 00:03:23.444
[PLAYING PIANO]

00:08:29.830 --> 00:08:34.520
[APPLAUSE]

00:08:34.520 --> 00:08:35.539
Thank you, thank you.

00:08:38.366 --> 00:08:38.990
That was short.

00:08:38.990 --> 00:08:40.031
Maybe I'll play one more.

00:08:45.748 --> 00:08:48.742
[PLAYING PIANO]

00:13:26.685 --> 00:13:29.679
[APPLAUSE]

00:13:29.679 --> 00:13:30.930
Thank you.

00:13:30.930 --> 00:13:33.140
It's a great privilege
to play for all of you.

00:13:33.140 --> 00:13:36.050
And I know I have so many
friends in the audience, too.

00:13:36.050 --> 00:13:38.900
So, so much love around
me I can feel right now

00:13:38.900 --> 00:13:40.490
that it's really cheating.

00:13:40.490 --> 00:13:41.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:41.270 --> 00:13:41.895
You know?

00:13:41.895 --> 00:13:44.270
Everybody loves me already,
because I know so many people

00:13:44.270 --> 00:13:46.940
here that love me that--

00:13:46.940 --> 00:13:49.820
I thank you for coming,
and I thank those of you

00:13:49.820 --> 00:13:51.320
who don't know me for coming.

00:13:51.320 --> 00:13:53.360
And I thank you kids for coming.

00:13:53.360 --> 00:13:56.690
And Lucas has already
learned the main lesson.

00:13:56.690 --> 00:14:00.180
Because before we
started, I did a trick--

00:14:00.180 --> 00:14:02.390
I do a thing with
students, just to see

00:14:02.390 --> 00:14:04.850
if they can figure out their
relationship to music, right?

00:14:04.850 --> 00:14:07.460
So I said, OK, you know you're
going to play today, right?

00:14:07.460 --> 00:14:09.546
And usually they'll
go, like, what?

00:14:09.546 --> 00:14:10.420
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:10.420 --> 00:14:11.990
Me?

00:14:11.990 --> 00:14:13.620
Like, when?

00:14:13.620 --> 00:14:14.480
Now.

00:14:14.480 --> 00:14:15.912
Uh, what am I going to play?

00:14:15.912 --> 00:14:18.370
I usually go, oh, you know,
something you know really well.

00:14:18.370 --> 00:14:20.870
Then they go, oh.

00:14:20.870 --> 00:14:22.943
Because nobody knows
anything really well.

00:14:22.943 --> 00:14:23.617
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:23.617 --> 00:14:24.450
So that's the trick.

00:14:24.450 --> 00:14:26.158
And then I said, is
that the relationship

00:14:26.158 --> 00:14:28.460
you want to have with music
for the rest of your life?

00:14:28.460 --> 00:14:31.460
Something you have
to-- with consequences?

00:14:31.460 --> 00:14:33.470
I mean, one of the biggest
delusions about music

00:14:33.470 --> 00:14:35.410
is that there's consequences.

00:14:35.410 --> 00:14:37.400
It's only music.

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:41.790
And the verb "to
play" is a big clue.

00:14:41.790 --> 00:14:42.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:42.770 --> 00:14:46.610
I think you don't play painting,
and you don't play dance.

00:14:46.610 --> 00:14:48.530
Well, you do dance
dancing, that's nice.

00:14:48.530 --> 00:14:51.050
But it's the only
thing where you play.

00:14:51.050 --> 00:14:53.090
And I think that's a
big clue, you know?

00:14:53.090 --> 00:14:54.576
So anyway, he passed the test.

00:14:54.576 --> 00:14:55.700
I said, I was only kidding.

00:14:55.700 --> 00:14:57.741
I said, so you're going
to play it, right, Lucas?

00:14:57.741 --> 00:14:58.420
He says, yeah.

00:14:58.420 --> 00:15:00.080
Yeah, I want to play, yeah.

00:15:00.080 --> 00:15:00.920
I said, really?

00:15:00.920 --> 00:15:02.128
You're going to get up there?

00:15:02.128 --> 00:15:03.770
Yeah, man, let's go.

00:15:03.770 --> 00:15:07.190
That's the best lesson you can
learn that it would be better

00:15:07.190 --> 00:15:11.990
to play and sound terrible--
not that Lucas would--

00:15:11.990 --> 00:15:14.810
than to think of this
as some kind of test

00:15:14.810 --> 00:15:16.520
that you can pass and fail.

00:15:16.520 --> 00:15:21.380
That's a real perversion of
the gift of music, you know?

00:15:21.380 --> 00:15:23.900
So what Effortless Mastery--

00:15:23.900 --> 00:15:26.802
it kind of came about by
me just talking to people.

00:15:26.802 --> 00:15:29.010
And then people asked
questions, and I answered them.

00:15:29.010 --> 00:15:30.050
Next thing you know
I was teaching,

00:15:30.050 --> 00:15:31.130
and then I was lecturing.

00:15:31.130 --> 00:15:34.010
And now I have my own
Institute at Berklee College

00:15:34.010 --> 00:15:37.240
of Music in Boston called the
Effortless Mastery Institute.

00:15:37.240 --> 00:15:41.480
And the whole concept is
basically a lot of things

00:15:41.480 --> 00:15:43.670
that people in other
careers can relate to,

00:15:43.670 --> 00:15:45.780
for example, making mistakes.

00:15:45.780 --> 00:15:48.140
This is almost a cliche now.

00:15:48.140 --> 00:15:51.710
But perfection, to me, is
celebrating the mistakes.

00:15:51.710 --> 00:15:53.900
The idea of avoiding
mistakes may

00:15:53.900 --> 00:15:58.910
be the thing that makes you miss
the most important discovery,

00:15:58.910 --> 00:15:59.480
you know?

00:15:59.480 --> 00:16:01.160
So when you touch the
instrument, trying

00:16:01.160 --> 00:16:04.190
to avoid mistakes, it's kind
of like touching a hot stove,

00:16:04.190 --> 00:16:04.970
you know?

00:16:04.970 --> 00:16:08.360
But if you touch the instrument
celebrating mistakes,

00:16:08.360 --> 00:16:10.820
it's more like putting
your hands in warm water,

00:16:10.820 --> 00:16:12.260
and you go, ah.

00:16:12.260 --> 00:16:15.290
Really, this should feel--
and it's not just the piano.

00:16:15.290 --> 00:16:18.110
Every instrument, when
the body forms a relation

00:16:18.110 --> 00:16:21.650
to the instrument, now you
have your real purpose.

00:16:21.650 --> 00:16:25.100
It's this instrument that
plays that instrument.

00:16:25.100 --> 00:16:27.420
And really, it's such
a neat thing to know.

00:16:27.420 --> 00:16:29.049
For example, this
sound, you know.

00:16:29.049 --> 00:16:32.043
[CRASHING PIANO CHORD]

00:16:35.780 --> 00:16:37.780
Sorry, I just have to
take that in for a second.

00:16:41.370 --> 00:16:44.280
That's such a great
sound, isn't it?

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:45.887
But you don't think of it.

00:16:45.887 --> 00:16:47.470
It's a piano, and I
put my hand on it.

00:16:47.470 --> 00:16:50.338
[CRASHING PIANO CHORD]

00:16:55.130 --> 00:16:57.510
But just think-- let's say
you were in your kitchen,

00:16:57.510 --> 00:16:59.176
and you kicked your
stove, and it went--

00:16:59.176 --> 00:17:01.864
[CRASHING PIANO CHORD]

00:17:05.560 --> 00:17:07.930
You'd be going in the kitchen
kicking your stove all

00:17:07.930 --> 00:17:08.430
the time.

00:17:08.430 --> 00:17:09.349
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:09.349 --> 00:17:10.890
You'd be calling
your friends saying,

00:17:10.890 --> 00:17:13.780
man, you got to come over
to hear my stove, wow.

00:17:13.780 --> 00:17:16.310
We don't realize the miracle.

00:17:16.310 --> 00:17:18.310
Well, in every way we
don't realize the miracle

00:17:18.310 --> 00:17:20.349
that we're in every moment.

00:17:20.349 --> 00:17:23.514
And I address it with music,
because I have kind of

00:17:23.514 --> 00:17:24.680
gotten it together in music.

00:17:24.680 --> 00:17:27.369
But like you all, I'm a
student of it in life.

00:17:27.369 --> 00:17:32.230
But I feel like I have a
lot I can pass on to you

00:17:32.230 --> 00:17:34.190
from the musical point of view.

00:17:34.190 --> 00:17:36.700
And one of the things is
to celebrate your mistakes.

00:17:36.700 --> 00:17:38.170
That is perfection.

00:17:38.170 --> 00:17:42.910
Another thing is to start from
nowhere, not trying to do it--

00:17:42.910 --> 00:17:45.230
I was talking to someone
before, and they said,

00:17:45.230 --> 00:17:47.380
I'd really like to
apply effortless mastery

00:17:47.380 --> 00:17:48.840
to my writing.

00:17:48.840 --> 00:17:50.679
And I said, it's
really this simple.

00:17:50.679 --> 00:17:52.720
You're only having trouble
writing because you're

00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:54.640
trying to write something good.

00:17:54.640 --> 00:17:55.450
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:55.450 --> 00:17:58.024
Write something bad,
you'll be writing all day.

00:17:58.024 --> 00:17:59.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:59.680 --> 00:18:02.410
You'll just fill page
after page, you know?

00:18:02.410 --> 00:18:04.690
And that's a good way
to approach anything.

00:18:04.690 --> 00:18:12.207
It is the fear of mistakes that
actually stunts the creativity.

00:18:12.207 --> 00:18:14.540
And a lot of people say, I
want to let go of that stuff,

00:18:14.540 --> 00:18:16.639
and OK, they really do,
but they really don't.

00:18:16.639 --> 00:18:19.180
Because a lot of times, you'll
play this sort of new age game

00:18:19.180 --> 00:18:21.790
with yourself, saying,
OK, I give everything

00:18:21.790 --> 00:18:26.410
up to the power or whatever, the
higher power, the grand poobah.

00:18:26.410 --> 00:18:31.210
And I turn all the
results over, and I just

00:18:31.210 --> 00:18:32.230
give gratitude, right?

00:18:32.230 --> 00:18:35.280
And you're sitting there like
this, and then look like--

00:18:35.280 --> 00:18:36.650
did my abundance come yet?

00:18:36.650 --> 00:18:37.562
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:37.562 --> 00:18:38.980
Is it here yet?

00:18:38.980 --> 00:18:42.020
Because if I surrender, the
abundance is supposed to come,

00:18:42.020 --> 00:18:43.630
but that's not surrender.

00:18:43.630 --> 00:18:45.370
I mean, surrender is really--

00:18:45.370 --> 00:18:51.200
it goes good, it goes
bad, it doesn't matter.

00:18:51.200 --> 00:18:53.990
I mean, that's the only
way it becomes really real.

00:18:53.990 --> 00:18:58.130
There are three forms of action
that I like to talk about.

00:18:58.130 --> 00:19:00.980
Two of them are a success,
and one is a failure.

00:19:00.980 --> 00:19:02.915
One is, let's say--

00:19:02.915 --> 00:19:04.290
well, I'll give
the best example.

00:19:04.290 --> 00:19:06.230
Musicians may live
in a certain town.

00:19:06.230 --> 00:19:09.380
And there's one club in
town that if you play there,

00:19:09.380 --> 00:19:10.350
you're a professional.

00:19:10.350 --> 00:19:13.250
And if you don't get a gig
there, you're still an amateur.

00:19:13.250 --> 00:19:16.220
So people will be meaning to
call that club all the time,

00:19:16.220 --> 00:19:18.420
and they never quite get
around to it, you know?

00:19:18.420 --> 00:19:20.700
Because they're
afraid of the answer.

00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:25.490
So in that situation,
there are three actions.

00:19:25.490 --> 00:19:27.470
Two of them are a success,
and one's a failure.

00:19:27.470 --> 00:19:30.740
One, you call the club,
the guy hires you--

00:19:30.740 --> 00:19:32.390
success.

00:19:32.390 --> 00:19:35.870
Two, you call the club,
the guy doesn't hire you--

00:19:35.870 --> 00:19:37.620
success.

00:19:37.620 --> 00:19:42.400
Three, you don't call the club
because he might not hire you.

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:44.710
That's a failure.

00:19:44.710 --> 00:19:46.720
Do you guys get that?

00:19:46.720 --> 00:19:49.670
So an action taken is a success.

00:19:49.670 --> 00:19:53.540
An action not taken because
you're afraid you'll fail

00:19:53.540 --> 00:19:55.061
is a failure.

00:19:55.061 --> 00:19:57.560
If you could get that straight--
and I mean, for all of us--

00:19:57.560 --> 00:20:01.460
if we could get that
straight in our experiments--

00:20:01.460 --> 00:20:04.430
I don't know what kind
of work you guys do here.

00:20:04.430 --> 00:20:08.025
Like Bradley outed me, I'm
not a computer scientist.

00:20:08.025 --> 00:20:10.110
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:10.110 --> 00:20:12.530
So I don't have any
idea what you do.

00:20:12.530 --> 00:20:14.630
But I do know that
your state of mind

00:20:14.630 --> 00:20:18.620
will absolutely make
the whole difference.

00:20:18.620 --> 00:20:24.170
For example, with musicians,
the basis of effortless mastery

00:20:24.170 --> 00:20:25.280
is this.

00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:28.940
Most of our problems are
in our thoughts, you know?

00:20:28.940 --> 00:20:30.530
A musician wakes
up-- and people think

00:20:30.530 --> 00:20:33.200
that musicians are special
because they're musicians.

00:20:33.200 --> 00:20:35.090
Let me tell you,
that's not the case.

00:20:35.090 --> 00:20:37.970
Musicians are at least as
neurotic as everybody else,

00:20:37.970 --> 00:20:39.050
easily.

00:20:39.050 --> 00:20:41.592
A musician who gets into a cab,
and he sits there in the cab,

00:20:41.592 --> 00:20:43.674
and the cab driver says,
so what do you do, buddy?

00:20:43.674 --> 00:20:44.780
He goes, I'm a musician.

00:20:44.780 --> 00:20:45.960
You can always see
it, the cab driver

00:20:45.960 --> 00:20:47.340
looks in the rear view mirror.

00:20:47.340 --> 00:20:50.090
Oh, he's a musician, oh, wow.

00:20:50.090 --> 00:20:51.980
And then they tell you
they played the piano

00:20:51.980 --> 00:20:55.430
when they were 11.

00:20:55.430 --> 00:20:57.950
And he's thinking, god,
all I do is drive this cab,

00:20:57.950 --> 00:20:59.690
and this guy is a musician.

00:20:59.690 --> 00:21:02.020
And the musician's sitting
in the backseat going,

00:21:02.020 --> 00:21:04.100
god, I wish all I had to
do is drive a cab, man.

00:21:04.100 --> 00:21:04.840
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:04.840 --> 00:21:06.590
It would be so much simpler.

00:21:06.590 --> 00:21:08.280
My life would be
so much simpler.

00:21:08.280 --> 00:21:11.510
So believe me, everybody
suffers from being in one place

00:21:11.510 --> 00:21:13.610
and thinking they should
be somewhere else.

00:21:13.610 --> 00:21:16.100
It's a pretty common thing.

00:21:16.100 --> 00:21:17.600
But the basis of
effortless mastery

00:21:17.600 --> 00:21:20.670
is that most of those
problems are in our thoughts.

00:21:20.670 --> 00:21:23.900
So for example, you
could be walking down

00:21:23.900 --> 00:21:25.570
the street on a
beautiful sunny day,

00:21:25.570 --> 00:21:27.195
and a musician will
do this to himself.

00:21:27.195 --> 00:21:29.270
Oh, it's a great day,
man, I feel so good.

00:21:29.270 --> 00:21:31.196
I really should practice more.

00:21:31.196 --> 00:21:32.110
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:32.110 --> 00:21:34.520
And now it's not such
a nice day anymore.

00:21:34.520 --> 00:21:37.010
Or if it is, they don't
notice it anymore.

00:21:37.010 --> 00:21:39.080
I know I've walked on
the beach in Hawaii

00:21:39.080 --> 00:21:41.288
and continued to be imprisoned
because of something I

00:21:41.288 --> 00:21:43.670
was thinking about.

00:21:43.670 --> 00:21:45.800
Everybody kind of knows
about that, right?

00:21:45.800 --> 00:21:49.490
So in music, I said
we want to transition

00:21:49.490 --> 00:21:52.640
out of the conscious mind
where all the thoughts are

00:21:52.640 --> 00:21:55.290
and into what I call the space.

00:21:55.290 --> 00:22:00.650
Now, every religion, and
every path, and psychology,

00:22:00.650 --> 00:22:03.150
and neuroscience
has a name for this.

00:22:03.150 --> 00:22:06.170
I just call it the space,
the space beyond, above,

00:22:06.170 --> 00:22:10.059
below, aside, wherever you see
it, beyond the conscious mind.

00:22:10.059 --> 00:22:12.350
Because most of the problems
are in the conscious mind.

00:22:12.350 --> 00:22:14.750
We are small because
of the thoughts

00:22:14.750 --> 00:22:16.790
we have in our conscious mind.

00:22:16.790 --> 00:22:21.180
Like, I'm not very
talented is a thought.

00:22:24.480 --> 00:22:27.182
So I might as well
say I'm a genius.

00:22:27.182 --> 00:22:28.890
I don't know which
one is true, but which

00:22:28.890 --> 00:22:30.760
one will get me more mileage?

00:22:30.760 --> 00:22:32.140
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:32.140 --> 00:22:33.175
You know?

00:22:33.175 --> 00:22:35.550
But there's the other thing
that's coming from the space.

00:22:35.550 --> 00:22:39.682
The space is a place where it's
not your mind playing anymore,

00:22:39.682 --> 00:22:41.640
or it's not your my
writing, or it's not your--

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:43.540
I mean, it is part
of your mind, but not

00:22:43.540 --> 00:22:45.550
that part you identify
as a conscious mind.

00:22:45.550 --> 00:22:46.270
[PLAYS PIANO]

00:22:46.270 --> 00:22:48.190
So right now, I'm
really talking to you.

00:22:48.190 --> 00:22:50.860
And I'm concentrating
on talking to you.

00:22:50.860 --> 00:22:54.880
And if anything, I'm even more
concentrated on talking to you

00:22:54.880 --> 00:22:56.830
while my hand is
playing the piano.

00:23:01.290 --> 00:23:06.710
So from the space, I don't play
the piano, my hand plays it.

00:23:06.710 --> 00:23:08.700
There's so many
benefits to that.

00:23:08.700 --> 00:23:12.280
And I believe that this is
a therapy for non-musicians.

00:23:12.280 --> 00:23:14.370
Put a person's hand on
a piano and just commit

00:23:14.370 --> 00:23:16.890
to pressing the buttons.

00:23:16.890 --> 00:23:19.690
But as you hear the sound,
instead of you thinking,

00:23:19.690 --> 00:23:23.970
what am I doing playing
the piano, you go,

00:23:23.970 --> 00:23:26.771
that's the most beautiful
sound I've ever heard.

00:23:26.771 --> 00:23:28.437
[PLAYS PIANO]

00:23:28.437 --> 00:23:29.770
And you're kind of in the space.

00:23:32.397 --> 00:23:34.730
And then it begs sort of the
spiritual question-- that's

00:23:34.730 --> 00:23:36.146
where the spiritual
part comes in.

00:23:36.146 --> 00:23:40.111
Because if I'm not
playing, who's playing?

00:23:40.111 --> 00:23:42.395
[PLAYS PIANO]

00:23:42.395 --> 00:23:44.520
And it doesn't matter how
you answer that question.

00:23:47.255 --> 00:23:49.630
But as long as you answer it
to what makes sense for you,

00:23:49.630 --> 00:23:52.960
sort of a higher power
of your understanding,

00:23:52.960 --> 00:23:54.820
or a power beyond
the conscious mind,

00:23:54.820 --> 00:23:56.770
that power will take over.

00:23:56.770 --> 00:24:00.730
And once it takes over,
there are no mistakes.

00:24:00.730 --> 00:24:03.610
Once that power takes
over, every sound

00:24:03.610 --> 00:24:06.400
is the most beautiful
sound I ever heard,

00:24:06.400 --> 00:24:08.914
and I don't have to
make choices anymore.

00:24:08.914 --> 00:24:11.330
Now, it doesn't excuse you
from practicing the instrument,

00:24:11.330 --> 00:24:13.705
for those of you young guys
saying, oh, wow, that's all I

00:24:13.705 --> 00:24:14.360
have to do?

00:24:14.360 --> 00:24:15.285
That's great.

00:24:15.285 --> 00:24:16.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:16.300 --> 00:24:18.680
I would be hopeful if
I was you right now.

00:24:18.680 --> 00:24:21.725
But the thing is,
I balance that--

00:24:21.725 --> 00:24:23.600
and I won't have time
to talk about it today,

00:24:23.600 --> 00:24:25.190
I want to talk more
about the space.

00:24:25.190 --> 00:24:27.830
I balance it with a method
of practicing that is

00:24:27.830 --> 00:24:31.339
so clear and so finite--

00:24:31.339 --> 00:24:33.380
like, one thing I can tell
you, even for teachers

00:24:33.380 --> 00:24:36.170
and everything, the larger
the swath of material

00:24:36.170 --> 00:24:38.600
you have to study,
the less likely

00:24:38.600 --> 00:24:41.300
you are ever to play it well.

00:24:41.300 --> 00:24:44.780
The smaller the example, the
more you can go into the space

00:24:44.780 --> 00:24:46.080
and master it.

00:24:46.080 --> 00:24:47.510
And why do you
want to master it?

00:24:47.510 --> 00:24:51.514
Because even if you're playing
something highly complex,

00:24:51.514 --> 00:24:52.430
it has to play itself.

00:24:52.430 --> 00:24:53.954
[PLAYS PIANO]

00:24:53.954 --> 00:24:55.370
So then you can
go into this space

00:24:55.370 --> 00:24:56.703
where you can receive the music.

00:24:56.703 --> 00:24:58.130
So I'm just dropping my--

00:24:58.130 --> 00:25:01.290
I forgot I was
dropping my fingers.

00:25:01.290 --> 00:25:03.630
It's a great thing to feel
like you're not doing it.

00:25:03.630 --> 00:25:05.380
Someone comes up to
you after the concert,

00:25:05.380 --> 00:25:07.730
they say, man,
you really sucked.

00:25:07.730 --> 00:25:09.765
I go, wasn't me.

00:25:09.765 --> 00:25:10.655
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:10.655 --> 00:25:12.440
[PLAYS PIANO]

00:25:12.440 --> 00:25:13.910
Don't blame me.

00:25:13.910 --> 00:25:15.350
(SINGING) Don't blame me.

00:25:15.350 --> 00:25:16.780
That's a good song.

00:25:16.780 --> 00:25:18.350
Was that a raised hand?

00:25:18.350 --> 00:25:20.420
OK.

00:25:20.420 --> 00:25:25.500
But I mean, effortless mastery
means precision with ease.

00:25:25.500 --> 00:25:28.770
So if you're a
computer scientist,

00:25:28.770 --> 00:25:33.060
you train the way a monk study
scriptures over and over again.

00:25:33.060 --> 00:25:35.180
You train with
complete devotion,

00:25:35.180 --> 00:25:38.110
but you perform with
complete detachment.

00:25:38.110 --> 00:25:40.290
And if you can get
those two things going,

00:25:40.290 --> 00:25:43.038
you can do something
really profound.

00:25:43.038 --> 00:25:46.440
[PLAYS PIANO]

00:25:46.440 --> 00:25:48.510
There's all sorts
of lessons that I

00:25:48.510 --> 00:25:52.920
learned from that kind
of detachment, you know?

00:25:52.920 --> 00:25:57.880
For example, for one
thing, I did my studies

00:25:57.880 --> 00:26:00.750
so I could do the same thing
I just did from the space

00:26:00.750 --> 00:26:02.190
but play something
highly complex.

00:26:02.190 --> 00:26:03.900
So let me just try that.

00:26:03.900 --> 00:26:06.390
Now that I said that, my
mind wants to go, oh, yeah,

00:26:06.390 --> 00:26:07.570
who are you kidding?

00:26:07.570 --> 00:26:08.070
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:08.070 --> 00:26:09.750
Man, now you've got to do that.

00:26:09.750 --> 00:26:13.530
But luckily, the space
is what Lucas said.

00:26:13.530 --> 00:26:14.732
Yeah, let's do it.

00:26:19.692 --> 00:26:22.668
[PLAYING PIANO]

00:26:56.396 --> 00:26:58.410
[APPLAUSE]

00:26:58.410 --> 00:27:01.020
It happens, but you need to take
that technology to the level

00:27:01.020 --> 00:27:02.460
of effortless mastery.

00:27:02.460 --> 00:27:05.500
It has to be
effortlessly absorbed,

00:27:05.500 --> 00:27:07.980
which is why the smaller
the amount of material,

00:27:07.980 --> 00:27:09.870
the more possible
it is to absorb it.

00:27:09.870 --> 00:27:12.840
And that has a collateral effect
on everything in your playing.

00:27:12.840 --> 00:27:17.820
But the same thing works
for any walk of life.

00:27:17.820 --> 00:27:21.180
But the first thing is learning
to respect the space above all

00:27:21.180 --> 00:27:23.810
else.

00:27:23.810 --> 00:27:25.970
Sorry, this keeps going out.

00:27:25.970 --> 00:27:27.746
Practicing doing
things from the space--

00:27:27.746 --> 00:27:29.120
when you're
practicing the space,

00:27:29.120 --> 00:27:31.440
you have to allow for mistakes.

00:27:31.440 --> 00:27:33.080
So if you're
writing, or whatever

00:27:33.080 --> 00:27:37.760
it is computer scientists
do, do it from the space,

00:27:37.760 --> 00:27:40.190
and let it go as wrong
as it needs to go.

00:27:40.190 --> 00:27:43.160
And if nothing else,
it stretches the mind

00:27:43.160 --> 00:27:47.480
to be extremely fertile when
it's time to be more exact.

00:27:47.480 --> 00:27:51.290
And not only that, it is
like irrigating creativity.

00:27:51.290 --> 00:27:54.512
Creativity is receiving
whatever's coming.

00:27:54.512 --> 00:27:57.290
[CRASHING PIANO CHORD]

00:27:57.290 --> 00:27:58.760
I mean, you can
have a limited form

00:27:58.760 --> 00:28:01.659
of creativity by
trying to control it

00:28:01.659 --> 00:28:02.700
right from the beginning.

00:28:02.700 --> 00:28:04.880
But if you receive it,
you'll find something's

00:28:04.880 --> 00:28:06.020
flowing through you.

00:28:06.020 --> 00:28:07.950
This is the ultimate creativity.

00:28:07.950 --> 00:28:10.550
This is probably the
value of musicians,

00:28:10.550 --> 00:28:14.210
or certain musicians, talking to
people in other walks of life,

00:28:14.210 --> 00:28:17.270
and helping them find that
flow within themselves.

00:28:17.270 --> 00:28:19.250
And in order to find
that flow, you just

00:28:19.250 --> 00:28:20.630
have to surrender the results.

00:28:20.630 --> 00:28:22.430
I know you hear
that all the time,

00:28:22.430 --> 00:28:26.960
but really, maybe you can't
do that when the money is

00:28:26.960 --> 00:28:28.160
on the line or whatever.

00:28:28.160 --> 00:28:29.840
But you can always
take some time

00:28:29.840 --> 00:28:32.060
and practice the
flow at the expense

00:28:32.060 --> 00:28:36.050
of playing the right notes
or doing the right things.

00:28:36.050 --> 00:28:39.050
And if you do that, you
expand your mind, you create,

00:28:39.050 --> 00:28:42.080
you make a greater
fertilization of creativity.

00:28:42.080 --> 00:28:45.650
You also have a lot
more self-generosity,

00:28:45.650 --> 00:28:47.160
which is really important.

00:28:47.160 --> 00:28:50.150
And if you beat
yourself up for failing,

00:28:50.150 --> 00:28:53.000
then you're going to
try harder not to fail.

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:55.780
Can everybody think
about when you try--

00:28:55.780 --> 00:28:57.110
I'll say this to musicians.

00:28:57.110 --> 00:28:59.484
Think about the time when you
really needed to play well.

00:28:59.484 --> 00:29:01.640
How did you play?

00:29:01.640 --> 00:29:04.670
Right, in your mind,
it was very important

00:29:04.670 --> 00:29:05.900
that you really score today.

00:29:05.900 --> 00:29:08.260
These people are listening,
and this guy's in the audience.

00:29:08.260 --> 00:29:09.650
And I want to play
with that guy.

00:29:09.650 --> 00:29:11.442
And I want the club
owner to hire me again.

00:29:11.442 --> 00:29:13.441
And then think about the
time when you were just

00:29:13.441 --> 00:29:15.702
fooling around, and for
some reason, in your mind,

00:29:15.702 --> 00:29:16.910
you didn't think it mattered.

00:29:16.910 --> 00:29:19.540
Then how'd you play?

00:29:19.540 --> 00:29:21.070
Better.

00:29:21.070 --> 00:29:22.540
Everybody says that.

00:29:22.540 --> 00:29:26.050
It's the same thing
with anything you do.

00:29:26.050 --> 00:29:29.350
If you're willing to
at least experiment

00:29:29.350 --> 00:29:33.920
with not needing to succeed
but connecting with the flow,

00:29:33.920 --> 00:29:36.560
you'll probably have an
awful lot of success.

00:29:36.560 --> 00:29:38.560
So those are the things
that are relative to it.

00:29:38.560 --> 00:29:41.790
The other lessons I learned
in music is that music works.

00:29:41.790 --> 00:29:43.560
It's people that mess it up.

00:29:43.560 --> 00:29:44.440
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:44.440 --> 00:29:45.790
Music works by itself.

00:29:45.790 --> 00:29:47.510
I wanted to show you something.

00:29:47.510 --> 00:29:49.482
This is a sort of
a harmony lesson.

00:29:49.482 --> 00:29:50.940
Now, you guys might
recognize that.

00:29:50.940 --> 00:29:51.481
I don't know.

00:29:51.481 --> 00:29:53.570
Do you study the modes?

00:29:53.570 --> 00:29:56.420
So you see Dorian,
Phrygian, Aeolian.

00:29:56.420 --> 00:29:58.350
Yeah, you all see it, right?

00:29:58.350 --> 00:30:00.850
Everybody thinks there's such
a thing as a right progression

00:30:00.850 --> 00:30:02.020
and a wrong progression.

00:30:02.020 --> 00:30:05.520
But how do you think you
find a new progression?

00:30:05.520 --> 00:30:07.330
Randomly.

00:30:07.330 --> 00:30:09.520
So let's try something random.

00:30:09.520 --> 00:30:10.750
I have a pen here.

00:30:10.750 --> 00:30:14.410
And you guys can see-- we'll
take the music students.

00:30:14.410 --> 00:30:17.590
[LAUGHTER] Somebody pick a note.

00:30:17.590 --> 00:30:18.430
AUDIENCE: G.

00:30:18.430 --> 00:30:19.665
KENNY WERNER: G?

00:30:19.665 --> 00:30:22.570
All right, I heard
G. And somebody

00:30:22.570 --> 00:30:26.175
pick one of those chords,
one of those modes.

00:30:26.175 --> 00:30:28.240
AUDIENCE: Dorian.

00:30:28.240 --> 00:30:30.850
KENNY WERNER: I heard
Dorian first, all right.

00:30:30.850 --> 00:30:32.424
Pick another note?

00:30:32.424 --> 00:30:33.270
AUDIENCE: C.

00:30:33.270 --> 00:30:37.850
KENNY WERNER: C. OK, sharps
and flats are OK too, guys.

00:30:37.850 --> 00:30:39.500
OK, C. Pick another chord there.

00:30:39.500 --> 00:30:40.250
AUDIENCE: Locrian.

00:30:40.250 --> 00:30:41.460
KENNY WERNER: Locrian.

00:30:41.460 --> 00:30:43.551
That's the one that
doesn't work so good.

00:30:43.551 --> 00:30:45.300
I knew I shouldn't
have written that down.

00:30:45.300 --> 00:30:46.560
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:46.560 --> 00:30:47.370
Pick another note.

00:30:47.370 --> 00:30:47.730
AUDIENCE: C flat.

00:30:47.730 --> 00:30:49.220
KENNY WERNER: F
sharp, thank you.

00:30:49.220 --> 00:30:51.074
That was a brilliant suggestion.

00:30:51.074 --> 00:30:51.626
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:51.626 --> 00:30:52.376
AUDIENCE: Aeolian.

00:30:52.376 --> 00:30:55.010
KENNY WERNER: Aeolian, that's
my favorite chord, Aeolian.

00:30:55.010 --> 00:30:56.010
You'll all recognize it.

00:30:56.010 --> 00:30:58.470
You may not have
known it as Aeolian.

00:30:58.470 --> 00:30:59.460
And one more note?

00:30:59.460 --> 00:31:00.330
AUDIENCE: B.

00:31:00.330 --> 00:31:01.470
KENNY WERNER: E flat.

00:31:01.470 --> 00:31:03.420
Sorry, the flat wins.

00:31:03.420 --> 00:31:06.550
Type of chord?

00:31:06.550 --> 00:31:07.640
Well, minor what?

00:31:07.640 --> 00:31:09.860
How about a major?

00:31:09.860 --> 00:31:12.100
The sharp 5 that I wrote wrong?

00:31:12.100 --> 00:31:12.850
AUDIENCE: Sus 4.

00:31:12.850 --> 00:31:16.360
KENNY WERNER: Lydian sus
4, E-flat major Lydian.

00:31:16.360 --> 00:31:19.000
OK, now, the base
notes were random.

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:20.860
The choice of chords was random.

00:31:20.860 --> 00:31:23.290
This should not work, right?

00:31:23.290 --> 00:31:24.150
It's all wrong.

00:31:24.150 --> 00:31:25.150
I mean, it's all random.

00:31:25.150 --> 00:31:26.941
So let's see what happens.

00:31:26.941 --> 00:31:27.690
It probably won't.

00:31:31.626 --> 00:31:34.578
[PLAYING PIANO]

00:31:50.322 --> 00:31:52.782
[APPLAUSE]

00:31:52.782 --> 00:31:56.490
All I did was obey one
of the most simple rules

00:31:56.490 --> 00:31:58.110
of music theory--

00:31:58.110 --> 00:31:59.410
voice leading.

00:31:59.410 --> 00:32:02.400
If the voices lead, you can
glue any two chords together.

00:32:02.400 --> 00:32:04.440
They could have no
relationship whatsoever.

00:32:04.440 --> 00:32:06.930
That's got to be
useful in other ways.

00:32:06.930 --> 00:32:09.930
But you have to have
the detachment to do it.

00:32:09.930 --> 00:32:12.510
You throw some stuff down, and
if you're immediately judging

00:32:12.510 --> 00:32:14.370
it, you're going to stop.

00:32:14.370 --> 00:32:16.177
So there's only one
kind of free music.

00:32:16.177 --> 00:32:17.760
You talk about free
music, it's like--

00:32:17.760 --> 00:32:20.500
[PLAYS WILD NOTES]

00:32:20.500 --> 00:32:22.510
There's really only
one kind of free music,

00:32:22.510 --> 00:32:25.720
music free from self-judgment.

00:32:25.720 --> 00:32:28.420
That is free music, and
it can be practiced.

00:32:28.420 --> 00:32:30.920
That's what the steps of
effortless mastery are about.

00:32:30.920 --> 00:32:32.770
So I thought we'd do
that little thing.

00:32:32.770 --> 00:32:37.890
And I want to give you another
example of a simple structure.

00:32:37.890 --> 00:32:40.300
But if you just
manipulate one thing,

00:32:40.300 --> 00:32:42.070
it becomes something original.

00:32:42.070 --> 00:32:44.200
So you know the
Simon and Garfunkel

00:32:44.200 --> 00:32:46.670
song, "Scarborough Fair?"

00:32:46.670 --> 00:32:48.257
So it goes like, you know--

00:32:48.257 --> 00:32:51.179
[PLAYING "SCARBOROUGH FAIR"]

00:32:59.470 --> 00:33:01.960
Now, that's not-- it's
a simple structure,

00:33:01.960 --> 00:33:03.700
but they changed one
thing, and that's

00:33:03.700 --> 00:33:05.450
why it is so distinctive.

00:33:05.450 --> 00:33:08.430
It should go like this.

00:33:08.430 --> 00:33:11.825
[PLAYING "SCARBOROUGH FAIR"]

00:33:15.705 --> 00:33:19.840
But because they delayed that
phrase, it became distinctive

00:33:19.840 --> 00:33:21.402
and will be forever.

00:33:21.402 --> 00:33:23.110
So sometimes you take
a simple structure,

00:33:23.110 --> 00:33:25.500
and you just do one
thing differently to it,

00:33:25.500 --> 00:33:27.340
and you have a
whole other world.

00:33:27.340 --> 00:33:29.800
These are the things we
experiment with in music.

00:33:29.800 --> 00:33:33.050
But the attitude of detachment--

00:33:33.050 --> 00:33:34.720
oh, it didn't go back, huh.

00:33:34.720 --> 00:33:36.160
There we go.

00:33:36.160 --> 00:33:39.430
The attitude of detachment is
what allows you to do that.

00:33:39.430 --> 00:33:42.670
You really deserve that.

00:33:42.670 --> 00:33:44.410
You really deserve that freedom.

00:33:44.410 --> 00:33:47.110
I'd rather come
from a random place

00:33:47.110 --> 00:33:50.350
and allow it to organize itself.

00:33:50.350 --> 00:33:52.570
And then how does
it organize itself?

00:33:52.570 --> 00:33:55.000
That's the spiritual
possibility.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:58.570
Maybe we are vehicles
for something, you know?

00:33:58.570 --> 00:34:00.700
But the only way you
could possibly even

00:34:00.700 --> 00:34:04.510
experiment with being a vehicle
is to let go of the control.

00:34:04.510 --> 00:34:06.520
I mean, we've heard
this everywhere, right?

00:34:06.520 --> 00:34:08.260
But let go of that
control, including

00:34:08.260 --> 00:34:10.090
the control of results.

00:34:10.090 --> 00:34:13.750
But really, let go of the
control of the results,

00:34:13.750 --> 00:34:14.530
you know?

00:34:14.530 --> 00:34:16.090
You can have fun in music--

00:34:16.090 --> 00:34:17.548
I'm going to say
this, and then I'm

00:34:17.548 --> 00:34:19.239
going to bring our
special guest up.

00:34:19.239 --> 00:34:23.350
But you can have fun with music
and not even know how to play.

00:34:23.350 --> 00:34:26.440
Did anyone ever see
the movie "Green Card?"

00:34:26.440 --> 00:34:29.429
It's this old movie, totally
forgettable movie with GÃ©rard

00:34:29.429 --> 00:34:31.270
Depardieu and Andie MacDowell.

00:34:31.270 --> 00:34:36.010
She is in New York,
going to places,

00:34:36.010 --> 00:34:39.429
trying to get money to put
atriums around New York City,

00:34:39.429 --> 00:34:40.000
right?

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:43.130
And he's this French guy she
knew who needs a green card.

00:34:43.130 --> 00:34:44.739
So they're living
together and trying

00:34:44.739 --> 00:34:48.290
to look like-- that's how
you can get a green card.

00:34:48.290 --> 00:34:52.150
But he's this gruff French
guy from Paris, stringy hair,

00:34:52.150 --> 00:34:55.449
and rolls his own cigarettes.

00:34:55.449 --> 00:34:57.160
And so there's this
one funny scene

00:34:57.160 --> 00:35:00.460
where she's in this Upper
East Side apartment talking

00:35:00.460 --> 00:35:03.700
to this woman about atriums,
and he lost his key,

00:35:03.700 --> 00:35:04.900
so he comes to meet her.

00:35:04.900 --> 00:35:07.240
And it's like, uh-oh, it's
like a bull in a china shop,

00:35:07.240 --> 00:35:08.020
you know?

00:35:08.020 --> 00:35:09.130
And so he comes in,
and he immediately

00:35:09.130 --> 00:35:10.390
starts rolling a cigarette.

00:35:10.390 --> 00:35:12.400
And in an Upper
East Side apartment,

00:35:12.400 --> 00:35:14.290
you do not even
smoke a cigarette,

00:35:14.290 --> 00:35:16.130
let alone roll
your own cigarette.

00:35:16.130 --> 00:35:17.350
So everything is going wrong.

00:35:17.350 --> 00:35:19.391
And then they go into the
living room for coffee,

00:35:19.391 --> 00:35:21.550
and he sees a piano.

00:35:21.550 --> 00:35:23.007
He goes, do you mind?

00:35:23.007 --> 00:35:24.340
You know, if he plays the piano?

00:35:24.340 --> 00:35:25.720
And this was a very hip moment.

00:35:25.720 --> 00:35:30.430
Because in fact, the avant
garde is very identified

00:35:30.430 --> 00:35:32.350
with Paris, the
Pierre Boulez school.

00:35:32.350 --> 00:35:34.370
And this could have
easily been the case.

00:35:34.370 --> 00:35:36.020
But he goes into
the living room,

00:35:36.020 --> 00:35:39.154
and he sits down at the
piano with this lady

00:35:39.154 --> 00:35:40.570
and Andie MacDowell
sitting there.

00:35:40.570 --> 00:35:41.320
And he does this.

00:35:41.320 --> 00:35:43.810
He goes--

00:35:43.810 --> 00:35:46.798
[CRASHING PIANO CHORDS]

00:35:59.280 --> 00:36:03.311
Even with the hair falling, like
the Beethoven look, you know?

00:36:03.311 --> 00:36:05.560
He gets done, and they show
a picture of the old lady,

00:36:05.560 --> 00:36:07.810
and she is in shock.

00:36:07.810 --> 00:36:11.490
Because she actually heard
music for the first time.

00:36:11.490 --> 00:36:14.680
And she probably had been to
the symphony and to the opera,

00:36:14.680 --> 00:36:17.380
but she just heard music
for the first time,

00:36:17.380 --> 00:36:19.270
experiencing his passion.

00:36:19.270 --> 00:36:22.470
But you don't actually know
if he can play the piano.

00:36:22.470 --> 00:36:23.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:23.290 --> 00:36:25.940
Isn't that kind of amazing?

00:36:25.940 --> 00:36:27.790
So anybody can
have this feeling.

00:36:27.790 --> 00:36:30.010
And I believe even
non-musicians,

00:36:30.010 --> 00:36:33.040
if they receive the sound,
and they use their hands

00:36:33.040 --> 00:36:35.230
to make the sound, they're
going to open a pathway

00:36:35.230 --> 00:36:37.590
to the heart and a pathway
to the brain that's

00:36:37.590 --> 00:36:39.424
going to have its effect
on everything else.

00:36:39.424 --> 00:36:41.214
And that's some of the
stuff I'm working on

00:36:41.214 --> 00:36:42.290
with effortless mastery.

00:36:42.290 --> 00:36:44.590
And that's the Effortless
Mastery Institute.

00:36:44.590 --> 00:36:46.540
So that's more or less the case.

00:36:46.540 --> 00:36:49.990
Now, I would like to bring
one more situation where

00:36:49.990 --> 00:36:56.890
complete random creativity just
might lead to music by bringing

00:36:56.890 --> 00:36:57.850
up to you--

00:36:57.850 --> 00:37:00.460
and I have to say, this is
one of the most brilliant

00:37:00.460 --> 00:37:01.630
performers I've ever met.

00:37:01.630 --> 00:37:03.174
I'll tell a quick
story about her.

00:37:03.174 --> 00:37:05.090
And I know, Claudia,
it's never exactly right,

00:37:05.090 --> 00:37:07.298
but I'm going to tell it
the way I know it, you know?

00:37:07.298 --> 00:37:08.700
She wanted me to--

00:37:08.700 --> 00:37:12.165
years ago-- do an album
with her, Claudia Villela.

00:37:12.165 --> 00:37:14.710
And so I came out.

00:37:14.710 --> 00:37:16.030
I don't know if we did gigs.

00:37:16.030 --> 00:37:18.040
We went right to the
studio, and we start.

00:37:18.040 --> 00:37:22.840
And then she told me also, she
said, I really need a stove,

00:37:22.840 --> 00:37:23.740
you know?

00:37:23.740 --> 00:37:25.150
She needs to buy a stove.

00:37:25.150 --> 00:37:26.830
And I'm starting,
like, feeling guilty.

00:37:26.830 --> 00:37:30.096
Oh, gosh, you're paying
me to make a record,

00:37:30.096 --> 00:37:31.720
but you kind of need
a stove, you know?

00:37:31.720 --> 00:37:33.969
So I said, so what kind of
music are we going to play?

00:37:33.969 --> 00:37:35.500
She said, no, no
music, we're just

00:37:35.500 --> 00:37:37.510
going to play free together.

00:37:37.510 --> 00:37:40.109
I went-- because not too
many people can do that.

00:37:40.109 --> 00:37:41.650
Because there are
not too many people

00:37:41.650 --> 00:37:43.960
that will give themselves
permission to do that.

00:37:43.960 --> 00:37:46.580
She says that, and I
don't even know her?

00:37:46.580 --> 00:37:50.090
I said, may I just suggest
you go buy a stove?

00:37:50.090 --> 00:37:50.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:50.890 --> 00:37:51.820
Don't do this.

00:37:51.820 --> 00:37:52.860
Go buy the stove.

00:37:52.860 --> 00:37:53.810
She said, no, no, no.

00:37:53.810 --> 00:37:54.310
It's cool.

00:37:54.310 --> 00:37:54.809
It's cool.

00:37:54.809 --> 00:37:56.530
And she just blew me away.

00:37:56.530 --> 00:38:03.190
She can make music from
this space at will,

00:38:03.190 --> 00:38:05.710
and that's not that easy.

00:38:05.710 --> 00:38:07.360
Claudia Villela.

00:38:07.360 --> 00:38:10.300
[APPLAUSE]

