00:48:08.880 --> 00:48:13.080
So my question-- and I
ask this to the hosts

00:48:13.080 --> 00:48:17.280
of every single talk or
performance that I go to.

00:48:17.280 --> 00:48:20.010
As far as creating
one's own music--

00:48:20.010 --> 00:48:23.880
what's your advice
for the general idea

00:48:23.880 --> 00:48:26.820
of finding your
sound and finding

00:48:26.820 --> 00:48:30.565
what seems most like you?

00:48:30.565 --> 00:48:32.395
KENNY WERNER: Is this working?

00:48:32.395 --> 00:48:33.360
Is that on?

00:48:33.360 --> 00:48:34.140
Yeah.

00:48:34.140 --> 00:48:37.020
You know, it's funny how people
say, how do I find my voice?

00:48:37.020 --> 00:48:39.540
You already have your voice.

00:48:39.540 --> 00:48:42.870
The way you find
your music is by stop

00:48:42.870 --> 00:48:45.000
expecting things of
yourself and start

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:47.640
to go towards the
sounds that attract you.

00:48:47.640 --> 00:48:49.140
And we are humans,
not computers,

00:48:49.140 --> 00:48:52.050
so it's only a few different
things that attract us.

00:48:52.050 --> 00:48:55.410
It's not like we have
thousands of different options.

00:48:55.410 --> 00:48:57.210
We're attracted to the
same sounds, sounds

00:48:57.210 --> 00:48:58.680
that make us start to vibrate.

00:48:58.680 --> 00:49:01.350
And as we choose those
sounds habitually,

00:49:01.350 --> 00:49:05.220
they become what other
people define as our voice.

00:49:05.220 --> 00:49:09.180
The hardest way to find your
voice is by looking for it.

00:49:09.180 --> 00:49:13.020
What should I be that
seems original, you know?

00:49:13.020 --> 00:49:16.540
And then this all-pervasive
thing, a need to sound good.

00:49:16.540 --> 00:49:19.410
See, that's the thing that if
we can take that out of it--

00:49:19.410 --> 00:49:22.140
musicians say, well, yeah, when
I play, I want to sound good.

00:49:22.140 --> 00:49:23.700
Sounds reasonable enough, right?

00:49:23.700 --> 00:49:25.997
But what if we were just
talking, and I said--

00:49:25.997 --> 00:49:26.705
what's your name?

00:49:26.705 --> 00:49:27.560
AUDIENCE: Gabriel.

00:49:27.560 --> 00:49:28.280
KENNY WERNER: Ariel?

00:49:28.280 --> 00:49:29.030
AUDIENCE: Gabriel.

00:49:29.030 --> 00:49:30.600
KENNY WERNER: Gabriel?

00:49:30.600 --> 00:49:32.577
When I talk to you,
what do you want?

00:49:32.577 --> 00:49:34.410
When you're talking,
what do you want to do?

00:49:34.410 --> 00:49:37.410
You say, Kenny, when I talk
to you, I want to sound good.

00:49:37.410 --> 00:49:38.160
AUDIENCE: I mean--

00:49:38.160 --> 00:49:38.640
KENNY WERNER: You
know what I mean?

00:49:38.640 --> 00:49:40.410
It's so irrelevant,
but in music, that's

00:49:40.410 --> 00:49:42.150
somehow acceptable.

00:49:42.150 --> 00:49:44.430
So go to the sounds
that attract you,

00:49:44.430 --> 00:49:46.300
and they'll attract
you all the time.

00:49:46.300 --> 00:49:48.870
And you'll develop
something within the sounds

00:49:48.870 --> 00:49:52.290
that attract you that will
be someone else identifying

00:49:52.290 --> 00:49:53.770
your voice.

00:49:53.770 --> 00:49:54.270
OK?

00:49:54.270 --> 00:49:56.421
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

00:49:56.421 --> 00:49:58.972
BRADLEY HOROWITZ:
Great question.

