while you cross the street.

00:50:36.090 --> 00:50:38.400
But it has an effect
on everything you do.

00:50:38.400 --> 00:50:44.340
So by practicing this open,
creative, self-generosity,

00:50:44.340 --> 00:50:46.020
you open to creative things.

00:50:46.020 --> 00:50:47.400
But very good question.

00:50:47.400 --> 00:50:50.520
Out in the world, you don't
try to do anything like that.

00:50:50.520 --> 00:50:54.390
You continue to study so
that the technology of what

00:50:54.390 --> 00:50:57.381
you're doing doesn't fail
you even if you are nervous.

00:50:57.381 --> 00:50:59.880
So for example, sometimes I'll
have people come play for me.

00:50:59.880 --> 00:51:02.130
And they'll say, I usually
play much better than that,

00:51:02.130 --> 00:51:02.890
but I was nervous.

00:51:02.890 --> 00:51:04.260
I said, well, that's not why.

00:51:04.260 --> 00:51:07.560
If you were nervous, and that's
why you made certain mistakes,

00:51:07.560 --> 00:51:10.660
why did you play anything right?

00:51:10.660 --> 00:51:14.320
Because some things are known so
well that they play themselves,

00:51:14.320 --> 00:51:15.260
and other things--

00:51:15.260 --> 00:51:17.080
what doesn't play right
when you're nervous

00:51:17.080 --> 00:51:19.030
or it doesn't work
right tells you

00:51:19.030 --> 00:51:20.380
you need more work on that area.

00:51:20.380 --> 00:51:21.689
Now, that's one part.

00:51:21.689 --> 00:51:22.480
The other part is--

00:51:22.480 --> 00:51:24.140
I'll just relate
it to you twice.

00:51:24.140 --> 00:51:26.810
Two classical musicians--
different, unrelated--

00:51:26.810 --> 00:51:28.810
called me and said, I've
been reading your book,

00:51:28.810 --> 00:51:29.620
and I love it.

00:51:29.620 --> 00:51:31.870
And I'm auditioning
for the first oboe

00:51:31.870 --> 00:51:33.520
chair of the Chicago Symphony.

00:51:33.520 --> 00:51:35.992
How do I do effortless mastery?

00:51:35.992 --> 00:51:37.450
And I said, well,
you don't exactly

00:51:37.450 --> 00:51:39.460
just do effortless mastery.

00:51:39.460 --> 00:51:41.430
You keep practicing
within yourself,

00:51:41.430 --> 00:51:43.714
and it more and more
over time shows up.

00:51:43.714 --> 00:51:45.130
But I will give
you an assignment.

00:51:45.130 --> 00:51:46.990
When you go to that
audition, no matter

00:51:46.990 --> 00:51:49.030
how it goes, whether you blew
it, whether you did great,

00:51:49.030 --> 00:51:50.350
whether you get
it or you don't, I

00:51:50.350 --> 00:51:51.790
want you to commit
to me right now

00:51:51.790 --> 00:51:54.560
you're going to go out
and celebrate afterwards.

00:51:54.560 --> 00:51:58.180
And if you celebrate afterwards,
regardless of the audition,

00:51:58.180 --> 00:52:00.080
you're doing effortless mastery.

00:52:00.080 --> 00:52:02.470
Because you're taking
away consequences.

00:52:02.470 --> 00:52:05.339
In both cases, they got it, but
they realized how loose they

00:52:05.339 --> 00:52:06.880
felt, because they
already knew there

00:52:06.880 --> 00:52:09.255
were going to go celebrate.

00:52:09.255 --> 00:52:11.255
So there's a couple of
thoughts on that subject.

00:52:11.255 --> 00:52:11.760
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:52:11.760 --> 00:52:12.551
KENNY WERNER: Yeah.

